-- Reductio ad Absurdum (Proof by Contradiction)
--
-- Classical: Assume ~A, derive contradiction, conclude A
-- CredTT: If ~A is Unstable0 (fragile near 0), then A is Stable1
--
-- Example: sqrt(2) irrationality (the classic reductio)
-- Assume sqrt(2) = p/q in lowest terms
-- Derive contradiction (p,q both even but gcd=1)
-- Conclude sqrt(2) is irrational

-- Classical reductio: ~A -> False, therefore A
-- CredTT reductio: Unstable0(~A) implies Stable1(A)

-- This is the STABILITY version of reductio:
-- Not "assume false, derive anything" but
-- "fragile negation implies robust positive"

-- Assume sqrt2 rational at credence c
postulate sqrt2_rational : sqrt2_is_rational @ c

-- Assume gcd = 1 (lowest terms) at credence c
postulate gcd_one : gcd_p_q_is_1 @ c

-- Derive p is even
derive p_even : p_is_even @ c from sqrt2_rational by algebra

-- Derive q is even (from p even)
derive q_even : q_is_even @ c from p_even by substitution

-- Derive gcd >= 2 (both even)
derive gcd_two : gcd_geq_2 @ c from q_even by both_even

-- CONTRADICTION: gcd=1 AND gcd>=2
contradict gcd_one gcd_two

-- After contradiction: c = 0
-- The assumption has credence ZERO

-- Therefore: negation has credence ONE
negate sqrt2_irrational from sqrt2_rational

-- The KEY insight:
-- Classical: "contradiction, therefore opposite"
-- CredTT: "credence forced to 0, therefore negation at credence 1"
--
-- The sqrt2_rational claim is UNSTABLE (c=0)
-- Therefore sqrt2_irrational is STABLE (c=1)

-- After contradiction, the negated claim has credence 1
-- Note: stability cannot be asserted directly because the original
-- credence was a variable. The result has credence 1 but Unknown stability
-- in the checker. This is a technical limitation that could be improved.
